Results and interpretation for the example
We display estimates using the three approaches for the EPObirth weight data from 110 DZ twin pairs in Table 1. In this example the estimated value of bW is considerably larger (more negative) than that of bB. A test that the two coefficients are equal reveals strong evidence against the null hypothesis (P 5 0.007 by likelihood ratio or Wald test), so the adjustment for pair-level factors (by way of the pair mean term) clearly improves the fit of the model. Further insight can be gained from the fact that the twin-specific deviation from the pair mean, Xi1 À Xi, can be re-expressed as half the difference between the two twin’s X values: Xi1À Xi ¼

ðXi1À Xi2Þ=2, so we are using both twins’ values in the model to estimate bW with a constraint that the effects are equal and opposite for each twin in a pair. The model-fitting results show that using Xij À Xi rather than simply the twin’s own value Xij as a single predictor provides a better fit to the data, indicating that the relative value of X within a twin pair is more useful in predicting Y than the absolute level of X.
In summary, fitting model (1) for the expected value of Y essentially ignores the pairing between the twins, fitting a standard linear regression that treats the twins ‘as individuals’.
